<ns0:graph edgedefault="undirected"><ns0:node id="Navy">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Navy</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">organization</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Navy is the government entity for which MCMC provides support in operational tests, equipment management, fiscal accounting, and supply chain activities.&lt;SEP&gt;The Navy is responsible for orders, directives, products, services, supply, maintenance administration, and watercraft maintenance in support of the MCPP contract.&lt;SEP&gt;Navy utilizes NTCSS applications for maintenance and logistics requirements in support of MCPP activities.&lt;SEP&gt;Navy issues instructions and manuals on transportation, medical logistics, product data reporting, and environmental readiness applicable to Marine Corps operations.&lt;SEP&gt;Navy receives reports, plans, estimates, and support services from MCMC, including crane operations, maintenance, and logistics for watercraft and prepositioning equipment.&lt;SEP&gt;Navy is involved in watercraft maintenance center operations and technical proposals.&lt;SEP&gt;Navy is referenced in technical methodologies and ACRNs for the Marine Corps Prepositioning Program.&lt;SEP&gt;Navy is the U.S. military organization associated with watercraft maintenance, ship readiness, exercise reports, and various operational support activities.&lt;SEP&gt;Navy is the United States Navy, referenced for ACRN funding sources and cost segregation processes.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-939c604b9027c9cc38a7fb31f4c86c29&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-28d6e3bcda588a7e152c62f52269f946&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-48caa545ec007aaf46c9abe9ec8c0c78&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-30e4e078d2ff5ac82b96140f8c79e3f2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1b912387d0abf83a18f9cd19906dc41e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f121013aeb8c98e8b0609d68d89b74e5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b8875a30a8284afacba5893b8971b2b3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bee5e6b5db1fe2dc611fc5fc2b227a51&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="NAV-P">
  <ns0:data key="d0">NAV-P</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">organization</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">NAV-P is the Navy point of contact or entity that approves requests, receives reports, and directs activities related to GFE, vehicles, and fiscal matters.&lt;SEP&gt;NAV-P is the Navy authority that approves plans, reports, inventory adjustments, and provides guidance on supply matters.&lt;SEP&gt;NAV-P is the Navy entity receiving reports, approvals, and coordination for logistics operations from the MCMC.&lt;SEP&gt;NAV-P approves shortages, provides guidance on packaging and locations, receives reports and logs from MCMC, and authorizes repairs.&lt;SEP&gt;NAV-P is the government entity that approves actions, receives reports, and directs tasks related to Navy Watercraft maintenance, including notifications, reviews, and assignments of priorities.&lt;SEP&gt;NAV-P provides requirements, information, and direction for MCMC services related to external contracts and watercraft support.&lt;SEP&gt;NAV-P is the entity to which reports and schedules are submitted, and it provides approvals and requirements for maintenance activities.&lt;SEP&gt;NAV-P directs and approves maintenance tasks, receives reports, and provides schedules for Navy Watercraft operations.&lt;SEP&gt;NAV-P is Navy Prepositioning Department responsible for oversight and notifications.&lt;SEP&gt;NAV-P receives notifications for WHE inspections, tests, accidents, near misses, approves Inspection and Usage Program, and is involved in scheduling around ship evolutions and weather.&lt;SEP&gt;NAV-P is the Navy Prepositioning entity overseeing CESE, providing technical direction and receiving reports.&lt;SEP&gt;NAV-P receives Detailed Reports of Findings, Corrective Maintenance Memos, scopes of work, estimates, and weekly Repair Logs from MCMC.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-955c2fafc0e5a2a07e97130b42a872b5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f808346dbf233cd47e4c673a7cf87022&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-48caa545ec007aaf46c9abe9ec8c0c78&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d6887833d0f1a6398bb6c8fd6f72d5c8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5edf02307c6ad1788f6967955fbea6ff&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c2bae9a24e71825050f79fc141b2e181&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-85b50b451f72c11f155dc39b516d8dd3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e151c7682b4ed7c6cd2fcdc2e29ec22&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-93c4a54422e967728929a60f73e593e2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e73c8ab3a0b248cdeedb8496a5c6f8a9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7659b0abfc62a3f8f0edbf4a1fee058e</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Government Furnished Equipment (GFE)">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Government Furnished Equipment (GFE)</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">deliverable</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Government Furnished Equipment (GFE) consists of property provided by the Government to MCMC for contract performance, requiring accountability, maintenance, and reporting.&lt;SEP&gt;GFE is provided for contract performance and must be maintained in satisfactory condition using DPAS for accountability.&lt;SEP&gt;Government Furnished Equipment is provided by the government for maintenance, repair, and use by MCMC, with a list in Contract Attachment 6.a.&lt;SEP&gt;Government Furnished Equipment (GFE) includes Organic GFE and Non-PO equipment requiring PMCS, corrective maintenance, and adherence to applicable TMs and rosters.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-13a4841aefad66042f059edb023e607b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c12bdd730383e0d5968b0354d37c6d8a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b8875a30a8284afacba5893b8971b2b3</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Defense Property Accountability System (DPAS)">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Defense Property Accountability System (DPAS)</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">technology</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Defense Property Accountability System (DPAS) is the system used by MCMC to maintain accountability records for assigned Navy GFE in accordance with SECNAVINST 7320.10A.&lt;SEP&gt;DPAS is used by MCMC to maintain strict accountability of assigned Navy Government Furnished Equipment in accordance with SECNAVINST 7320.10A.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b8875a30a8284afacba5893b8971b2b3</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="SECNAVINST 7320.10A">
  <ns0:data key="d0">SECNAVINST 7320.10A</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">SECNAVINST 7320.10A is the instruction guiding the maintenance of strict accountability of Navy GFE using DPAS.&lt;SEP&gt;SECNAVINST 7320.10A is a Secretary of the Navy instruction pertaining to logistics and supply chain processes.&lt;SEP&gt;SECNAVINST 7320.10A is a Secretary of the Navy instruction on financial liability and property accounting.&lt;SEP&gt;SECNAVINST 7320.10A provides instructions for maintaining accountability of Government Furnished Equipment using DPAS.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-c2bae9a24e71825050f79fc141b2e181&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e151c7682b4ed7c6cd2fcdc2e29ec22&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b8875a30a8284afacba5893b8971b2b3</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="DFARS 252.217-7028">
  <ns0:data key="d0">DFARS 252.217-7028</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">DFARS 252.217-7028 is the clause referenced for handling Over and Above Work Requests in the weekly Status and Progress Report.&lt;SEP&gt;DFARS 252.217-7028 governs prior authorization for Navy "Over and Above" tasks.&lt;SEP&gt;DFARS 252.217-7028 requires prior authorization for Navy "Over and Above" tasks.&lt;SEP&gt;DFARS 252.217-7028 is a Defense Federal Acquisition Regulation Supplement clause for over-and-above work.&lt;SEP&gt;DFARS 252.217-7028 is incorporated for authorizations to purchase/subcontract and over and above requirements.&lt;SEP&gt;DFARS 252.217-7028 governs over and above requirements for corrective maintenance on Navy CESE.&lt;SEP&gt;DFARS 252.217-7028 is the clause requiring prior authorization from the Contracting Officer for over and above tasks in corrective maintenance and corrosion control.&lt;SEP&gt;DFARS 252.217-7028 specifies reimbursement for contractor acquired materials on the basis of actual costs.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-955c2fafc0e5a2a07e97130b42a872b5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a9aba44b05f751488f4a50faebf206cb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1b912387d0abf83a18f9cd19906dc41e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d6887833d0f1a6398bb6c8fd6f72d5c8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b8875a30a8284afacba5893b8971b2b3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d89c19e067243fa311d34bfc3fa99c70&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f808346dbf233cd47e4c673a7cf87022</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="MCSF-BI Navy Point">
  <ns0:data key="d0">MCSF-BI Navy Point</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">location</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">MCSF-BI Navy Point is the designated area where MCMC plans and accomplishes staging and storage of Navy owned equipment and materiel.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="General Services Administration (GSA)">
  <ns0:data key="d0">General Services Administration (GSA)</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">organization</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">General Services Administration (GSA) is the entity providing fleet vehicles that MCMC must inspect, maintain, and operate in accordance with guidance.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="NAVSUP P-485">
  <ns0:data key="d0">NAVSUP P-485</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">NAVSUP P-485 is the publication outlining supply chain management functions, storage, and disposal procedures for Navy materiel.&lt;SEP&gt;NAVSUP P-485 is a supply manual referenced for inventory control, physical inventory procedures, requisitioning, receipt management, and compliance requirements.&lt;SEP&gt;NAVSUP P-485 is a Naval Supply Systems Command publication detailing supply systems management, receipt processing, and discrepancy handling.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-c2bae9a24e71825050f79fc141b2e181&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e151c7682b4ed7c6cd2fcdc2e29ec22&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="NAVSUP P-538">
  <ns0:data key="d0">NAVSUP P-538</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">NAVSUP P-538 is the publication requiring the use of the Operator's Daily Check List for Navy owned Material Handling Equipment.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="NAVSUP P-723">
  <ns0:data key="d0">NAVSUP P-723</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">NAVSUP P-723 is the publication governing the segregation, storage, and maintenance of Navy materiel by COSAL type.&lt;SEP&gt;NAVSUP P-723 is a supply instruction referenced for inventory management, physical inventory, and depot level repair processes.&lt;SEP&gt;NAVSUP P-723 is a Naval Supply Systems Command publication covering receipt management, validations, and reconciliations.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-c2bae9a24e71825050f79fc141b2e181&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e151c7682b4ed7c6cd2fcdc2e29ec22&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Coordinated Shipboard Allowance List (COSAL)">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Coordinated Shipboard Allowance List (COSAL)</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">concept</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Coordinated Shipboard Allowance List (COSAL) is the categorization system used to segregate and store Navy materiel by types such as NSE, NCE, and NBG.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="RSupply">
  <ns0:data key="d0">RSupply</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">technology</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">RSupply is the system in which MCMC documents and provides physical inventory control plan results for retail accounts.&lt;SEP&gt;RSupply is a supply management system used for inventory adjustments, reporting results, and processing requisitions and receipts.&lt;SEP&gt;RSupply is an application within NTCSS for supply functions, including ordering, receiving, issuing, and financial reconciliation.&lt;SEP&gt;RSupply is an application that provides personnel with tools for ordering, receiving, issuing services and materials, maintaining financial records, and reconciling supply, inventory, and financial records with shore infrastructure.&lt;SEP&gt;RSupply is a system into which KSDs supporting equipment transfers are uploaded.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-c2bae9a24e71825050f79fc141b2e181&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bee5e6b5db1fe2dc611fc5fc2b227a51&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-432adfa735f19522f81538c1e139e7a3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e73c8ab3a0b248cdeedb8496a5c6f8a9</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Global Combat Support System – Marine Corps (GCSS-MC)">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Global Combat Support System – Marine Corps (GCSS-MC)</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">technology</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Global Combat Support System – Marine Corps (GCSS-MC) is the system used alongside RSupply for reporting inventory results to the Government.&lt;SEP&gt;Global Combat Support System – Marine Corps (GCSS-MC) is a logistics system used for documenting and providing inventory results and uploading key supporting documents.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-c2bae9a24e71825050f79fc141b2e181&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="DoDI 5000.64">
  <ns0:data key="d0">DoDI 5000.64</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">DoDI 5000.64 is the instruction referenced in the annual Physical Inventory Control Plan submission requirements.&lt;SEP&gt;DoDI 5000.64 provides instructions on accountability of government property.&lt;SEP&gt;DoDI 5000.64 is a Department of Defense instruction on accountability of DoD equipment and other accountable property.&lt;SEP&gt;DoDI 5000.64 provides guidance on accountability and management of DoD equipment and other accountable property.&lt;SEP&gt;DoDI 5000.64 is the Accountability and Management of DoD Equipment and Other Accountable Property instruction applicable to MCMC property management.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-30e4e078d2ff5ac82b96140f8c79e3f2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-68739860c42b764e52f9649ea16ed702&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c2bae9a24e71825050f79fc141b2e181&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Status and Progress Report">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Status and Progress Report</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">deliverable</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Status and Progress Report is a weekly report provided by MCMC on all Navy work in progress, including subcontractor support, Over and Above Work Requests, and project-specific information, due no later than the close of business every Wednesday.&lt;SEP&gt;The weekly Status and Progress Report covers Navy work in progress, including "Over and Above" requests, due NLT close of business every Wednesday.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b8875a30a8284afacba5893b8971b2b3</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Physical Inventory Control Plan (PICP)">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Physical Inventory Control Plan (PICP)</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">deliverable</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Physical Inventory Control Plan (PICP) is an annual plan submitted by MCMC for inventory schedule and timelines, updated annually, in accordance with specified instructions.&lt;SEP&gt;Physical Inventory Control Plan (PICP) is an annual plan submitted as CDRL 5018, detailing inventory timelines and percentages for supply accounts.&lt;SEP&gt;Physical Inventory Control Plan (PICP) is an annual plan submitted as CDRL 6014, providing inventory schedules and timelines in accordance with specified instructions.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-c2bae9a24e71825050f79fc141b2e181&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-68739860c42b764e52f9649ea16ed702&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Navy Supply Center (NSC)">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Navy Supply Center (NSC)</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">organization</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Navy Supply Center (NSC) is the dedicated organization established and maintained by MCMC to perform supply chain management functions for Navy efforts.&lt;SEP&gt;NSC maintains occupational skill sets for supply chain, warehousing, and Capability Set (CAPSET) container production.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b8875a30a8284afacba5893b8971b2b3</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Section 6.A">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Section 6.A</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">section</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Section 6.A outlines MCMC responsibilities for personnel support, meetings, reporting, GFE accountability, vehicle maintenance, training, staging, and warranty claims for Navy operations.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Section 6.B">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Section 6.B</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">section</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Section 6.B delineates MCMC responsibilities for Navy fiscal requirements, including accounting, cost segregation, reporting, and reconciliations.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Section 6.C">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Section 6.C</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">section</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Section 6.C specifies MCMC duties for Navy supply chain, logistics, and warehousing, including establishing the NSC and managing materiel storage.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Operational Tests">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Operational Tests</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">event</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Operational Tests are activities supported by MCMC personnel through irregular hours, including Saturdays, Sundays, and shiftwork.&lt;SEP&gt;Operational Tests (OPTEST) are scheduled, supported, and documented by MCMC for Navy Watercraft, including technical refresh and major upgrades, with completed forms delivered within five calendar days.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-7659b0abfc62a3f8f0edbf4a1fee058e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Ship Offload/Backload Events">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Ship Offload/Backload Events</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">event</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Ship Offload/Backload Events are operational activities requiring MCMC support via flexible hours with Government approval.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Over and Above Work Requests">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Over and Above Work Requests</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">requirement</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Over and Above Work Requests are documented in the weekly Status and Progress Report in accordance with DFARS 252.217-7028, including routing status and progress percentage.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Contracting Officers Representative (COR)">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Contracting Officers Representative (COR)</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">person</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Contracting Officer’s Representative (COR) is the designated Navy official who receives notifications, directs repairs or replacements, signs RI designations, and reviews reports from MCMC.&lt;SEP&gt;The Contracting Officer’s Representative provides clarification on Navy requirements as needed and approves expenditures and deviations.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b8875a30a8284afacba5893b8971b2b3</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Accountable Property Officer (APO)">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Accountable Property Officer (APO)</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">person</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Accountable Property Officer (APO) is the Navy official responsible for concurring on RI designations, receiving inventory reports, and approving property acquisitions, transfers, losses, and dispositions.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Original Equipment Manufacturer (OEM)">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Original Equipment Manufacturer (OEM)</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">organization</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Original Equipment Manufacturer (OEM) is contacted by MCMC for warranty repair claims on defective Navy equipment under warranty coverage.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Material Handling Equipment (MHE)">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Material Handling Equipment (MHE)</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">technology</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Material Handling Equipment (MHE) is Navy-owned equipment for which MCMC uses the Operator's Daily Check List in accordance with NAVSUP P-538.&lt;SEP&gt;MHE is required for proper container movement to prevent damage during handling and storage.&lt;SEP&gt;Material Handling Equipment (MHE) is used by licensed operators for materiel and cargo handling in distribution operations.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-30ad74540c8224cf4aff1f3de36d3780&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e151c7682b4ed7c6cd2fcdc2e29ec22&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Operator's Daily Check List (ODCL)">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Operator's Daily Check List (ODCL)</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Operator's Daily Check List (ODCL) is used by MCMC for all Navy-owned MHE as required by NAVSUP P-538.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="DD Form 200">
  <ns0:data key="d0">DD Form 200</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">DD Form 200 is a form used to initiate the Financial Liability Investigation of Property Loss (FLIPL) process for lost, damaged, or destroyed government property.&lt;SEP&gt;DD Form 200 is a form accompanying voucher requests for physical loss adjustments where Marine Corps property was lost, damaged, or destroyed.&lt;SEP&gt;DD Form 200 is prepared and routed by the MCMC for lost, damaged, or destroyed Government property to initiate the Financial Liability Investigation of Property Loss process.&lt;SEP&gt;DD Form 200 is a form completed and submitted by MCMC if an item cannot be located, in accordance with MCO 4400.201, within 30 calendar days of identifying the missing item.&lt;SEP&gt;DD Form 200 is the Financial Liability Investigation of Property Loss form used to report all property losses related to GFE.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-a9aba44b05f751488f4a50faebf206cb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c2bae9a24e71825050f79fc141b2e181&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-65833c099ebcc7aa1fccc5a1d930a7aa&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bd3a05bb896b89de7fd366c654ad4a6b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="GSA Form 1627">
  <ns0:data key="d0">GSA Form 1627</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">GSA Form 1627 is part of the GSA Motor Vehicle Accident Reporting Kit completed by MCMC for reporting accidents involving Navy GSA Fleet vehicles.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Standard Form (SF) 91">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Standard Form (SF) 91</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Standard Form (SF) 91 is the GSA Motor Vehicle Accident Report completed for initial accident notifications on Navy GSA Fleet vehicles.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Standard Form (SF) 94">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Standard Form (SF) 94</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Standard Form (SF) 94 is the Statement of Witness form included in accident reporting for Navy GSA Fleet vehicles.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Actual Cost of Work Performed (ACWP) Report">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Actual Cost of Work Performed (ACWP) Report</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">deliverable</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Actual Cost of Work Performed (ACWP) Report is a joint stakeholders' report updated daily by MCMC for Navy efforts, including NSE, NCE, NBG, with corrections for errors within specified limits.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Navy End-of-Ship MPF Maintenance Cycle (MMC) Life Cycle Cost Report">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Navy End-of-Ship MPF Maintenance Cycle (MMC) Life Cycle Cost Report</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">deliverable</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Navy End-of-Ship MPF Maintenance Cycle (MMC) Life Cycle Cost Report details costs incurred for MMC and life cycle costs for Navy Watercraft, due NLT 60 calendar days after each MPS embarkation.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Status of Funds Report">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Status of Funds Report</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">deliverable</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Status of Funds Report (CDRL 5055) is a weekly report provided by MCMC including posted authorizations, obligations, balances, and credits.&lt;SEP&gt;Status of Funds Report is provided weekly by MCMC to NAV-P using Government-approved procedures, including posted authorizations, obligations, balances, allocations, and MRP credits.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-8a136ea2c9ab7ea9bb718fd0abd010d4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Estimate At Completion (EAC) Report">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Estimate At Completion (EAC) Report</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">deliverable</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Estimate At Completion (EAC) Report is submitted monthly by MCMC for Navy fiscal tracking, providing 12-month projections by CLIN with monthly breakdowns and prior actuals.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Navy Invoice Report">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Navy Invoice Report</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">deliverable</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Navy Invoice Report is a detailed monthly report provided by MCMC prior to payment submission, including labor, material, subcontract, and travel costs with backup documentation.&lt;SEP&gt;Navy Invoice Report is submitted monthly under section 6.B.7 for X002.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-aa9424078fa723e2caaae8aa59fb4397&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Contract Cost and Status Report (CCSR)">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Contract Cost and Status Report (CCSR)</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">deliverable</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Contract Cost and Status Report (CCSR) is an electronic monthly report for each Task Order, covering contract details, costs, funding, EAC, variances, and preparer information, commencing 30 days after contract award.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Job Order Number/Financial Information Pointer Annual Update">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Job Order Number/Financial Information Pointer Annual Update</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">deliverable</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Job Order Number/Financial Information Pointer Annual Update is provided annually by MCMC as part of required fiscal reports.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Follow-on Year EAC">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Follow-on Year EAC</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">deliverable</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Follow-on Year EAC is provided annually to the COR NLT 1 June of the current year for Navy fiscal projections.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="MCO P7300.21">
  <ns0:data key="d0">MCO P7300.21</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">MCO P7300.21 is the Marine Corps Financial Execution Standard Operating Procedures referenced for MCMC's financial oversight.&lt;SEP&gt;MCO P7300.21 is the Marine Corps Financial Execution Standard Operating Procedures referenced for preparing the CCSR.&lt;SEP&gt;MCO P7300.21 is the Marine Corps Financial Execution Standard Operating Procedures for fiscal management.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-8a136ea2c9ab7ea9bb718fd0abd010d4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-30ad74540c8224cf4aff1f3de36d3780&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="DoD FMR">
  <ns0:data key="d0">DoD FMR</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">DoD FMR is the Department of Defense Financial Management Regulations referenced for MCMC's fiscal responsibilities.&lt;SEP&gt;DoD FMR is the Department of Defense Financial Management Regulation ensuring compliance in receipt and financial processes.&lt;SEP&gt;DoD FMR is the Department of Defense Financial Management Regulations referenced in CCSR preparation.&lt;SEP&gt;DoD FMR is the Department of Defense Financial Management Regulations guiding fund accounting.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-c2bae9a24e71825050f79fc141b2e181&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-30ad74540c8224cf4aff1f3de36d3780&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8a136ea2c9ab7ea9bb718fd0abd010d4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="NAVFAC-P-300">
  <ns0:data key="d0">NAVFAC-P-300</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">NAVFAC-P-300 is the guideline followed by MCMC for redistribution and disposal of excess and obsolete Navy materiel.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="DD Form 1348-1">
  <ns0:data key="d0">DD Form 1348-1</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">DD Form 1348-1 is a form used for receipting Navy weapons, signed and submitted upon receipt.&lt;SEP&gt;DD Form 1348-1 is accurately completed and submitted by MCMC to support redistribution of Government-authorized excess Navy materiel.&lt;SEP&gt;DD Form 1348-1 is completed and submitted by MCMC for Navy CESE shipments and disposal.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-955c2fafc0e5a2a07e97130b42a872b5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e151c7682b4ed7c6cd2fcdc2e29ec22&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="DD Form 1149">
  <ns0:data key="d0">DD Form 1149</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">DD Form 1149 is used by MCMC for disposal processes in the redistribution of Navy materiel.&lt;SEP&gt;DD Form 1149 is a release/shipment document prepared for shipping, including manifests and bills of lading.&lt;SEP&gt;DD Form 1149 is used as an alternative to DD Form 1348-1 for receipting Navy weapons, signed and submitted upon receipt.&lt;SEP&gt;DD Form 1149 is completed and submitted by MCMC for Navy CESE redistribution and disposal.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-955c2fafc0e5a2a07e97130b42a872b5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-30ad74540c8224cf4aff1f3de36d3780&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e151c7682b4ed7c6cd2fcdc2e29ec22&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="MCO 4400.201">
  <ns0:data key="d0">MCO 4400.201</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">MCO 4400.201 is a Marine Corps order on management of property in the possession of the Marine Corps.&lt;SEP&gt;MCO 4400.201 is a Marine Corps Order providing guidance on supply management, validations, requisitions, and inventory procedures.&lt;SEP&gt;MCO 4400.201 is a Marine Corps Order on management of materiel and property accountability.&lt;SEP&gt;MCO 4400.201 is a Marine Corps Order providing guidelines for establishing physical locations for DSI inventories, referenced in volume 3, chapter 2.&lt;SEP&gt;MCO 4400.201 is a Marine Corps Order referenced for causative research, inventory adjustments, property records, and supply operations.&lt;SEP&gt;MCO 4400.201 is a Marine Corps order governing LTIs, repair cost estimates, and equipment disposition.&lt;SEP&gt;MCO 4400.201 is a Marine Corps order detailing procedures for requisitioning military equipment and other logistics activities.&lt;SEP&gt;MCO 4400.201 is a Marine Corps Order providing guidance on property accountability, inventory procedures, and chain of custody.&lt;SEP&gt;MCO 4400.201 outlines procedures for inventories, requisitions, and supply operations.&lt;SEP&gt;MCO 4400.201 is a Marine Corps Order referenced for inventory procedures, wall-to-wall inventories, and supply document retention.&lt;SEP&gt;MCO 4400.201 (Vol. 12) is a Marine Corps order for Class VIII management and sustainment that MCMC follows.&lt;SEP&gt;MCO 4400.201 is the Marine Corps Order referenced for providing PICP results in RSupply or GCSS-MC.&lt;SEP&gt;MCO 4400.201 is referenced for Limited Technical Inspections, condition codes, and disposition instructions for equipment.&lt;SEP&gt;MCO 4400.201 provides guidance on COSIS reporting, shelf life management, P3&amp;M, physical security, notifications, and inventory adjustments.&lt;SEP&gt;MCO 4400.201 outlines management of Demand-Supported Items inventories, including stockage criteria and storage guidelines.&lt;SEP&gt;MCO 4400.201 governs secondary reparable supply support to MAGTF during MPF exercises involving T-AKE ships.&lt;SEP&gt;MCO 4400.201 is the Intermediate Level Management Policy Manual that governs compliance for cyclic inventories of intermediate supply accounts.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-abd2ceb311ce78c8a8c1fe38d11ee4f4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a9aba44b05f751488f4a50faebf206cb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-67bad1bd73dd9a9a7549acb855ae5e55&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b6f17f0fbf6c678da23e588ab57f6900&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8a136ea2c9ab7ea9bb718fd0abd010d4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-22de15a10ae9bfba6096cca855d5f78a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-68739860c42b764e52f9649ea16ed702&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c2bae9a24e71825050f79fc141b2e181&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-65833c099ebcc7aa1fccc5a1d930a7aa&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bd3a05bb896b89de7fd366c654ad4a6b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-89b1a9fa6c0722adcd478e665df09141&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c10c3b1cc4c0a5d44aa2c137a52eaf0b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-432adfa735f19522f81538c1e139e7a3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a0a00a7bb666b381893da579a6b228c9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-583182dd35a85d121fe43aee2e3cd0eb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Independent Public Accountant (IPA)">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Independent Public Accountant (IPA)</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">organization</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Independent Public Accountant (IPA) conducts sample requirements to validate APSR accuracy as directed by higher headquarters.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Internal Controls and Audit Readiness Team (ICART)">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Internal Controls and Audit Readiness Team (ICART)</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">organization</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Internal Controls and Audit Readiness Team (ICART) performs periodic internal testing for APSR validation.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Naval Facilities Engineering Command (COMNAVFAC)">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Naval Facilities Engineering Command (COMNAVFAC)</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">organization</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Naval Facilities Engineering Command (COMNAVFAC) directs sample requirements for inventory and APSR accuracy validation.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Marine Corps Logistics Command (LOGCOM)">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Marine Corps Logistics Command (LOGCOM)</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">organization</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Marine Corps Logistics Command (LOGCOM) supports internal testing and sample requirements for APSR validation.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Shelf Life/Service Life Management">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Shelf Life/Service Life Management</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">concept</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Shelf Life/Service Life Management is developed and executed by MCMC for Navy materiel storage and maintenance.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c2c73655d1d9f038ea8945f49a05a1f</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Atomic Energy Act of 1954">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Atomic Energy Act of 1954</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">The Atomic Energy Act of 1954, as amended, serves as the basis for regulations on radioactive materials set forth in Title 10 of the Code of Federal Regulations.&lt;SEP&gt;The federal legislation, as amended, that governs the licensing of radioactive materials under regulations set forth in Title 10 of the Code of Federal Regulations.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-b535073f97c759a4e2ee7105ea8bc467&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Title 10 of the Code of Federal Regulations">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Title 10 of the Code of Federal Regulations</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Title 10 of the Code of Federal Regulations contains regulations on radioactive materials in effect on the date of the contract.&lt;SEP&gt;The title of the Code of Federal Regulations containing regulations issued pursuant to the Atomic Energy Act of 1954 for licensing radioactive materials.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-b535073f97c759a4e2ee7105ea8bc467&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Radioactive Material">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Radioactive Material</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">concept</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Radioactive material includes source material, special nuclear material, or by-product material regulated under the Atomic Energy Act of 1954 or other material with specific activity greater than 0.002 microcuries per gram or activity per item exceeding 0.01 microcuries.&lt;SEP&gt;Materials requiring specific licensing under the Atomic Energy Act of 1954 or with specific activity greater than 0.002 microcuries per gram or activity per item exceeding 0.01 microcuries.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-b535073f97c759a4e2ee7105ea8bc467&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Contracting Officer">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Contracting Officer</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">person</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">The Contracting Officer holds warrant authority to enter into, administer contracts, and issue directives.&lt;SEP&gt;Contracting Officer is a qualified individual with warrant authority to enter into, administer contracts, and make determinations about such contracts.&lt;SEP&gt;Contracting Officer receives notifications, approves corrective actions, identifies smoking areas, and reviews reports related to accidents and safety compliance.&lt;SEP&gt;Contracting Officer is a government personnel responsible for official notifications of discrepancies and unsatisfactory performance.&lt;SEP&gt;Contracting Officer is defined by the acronym KO.&lt;SEP&gt;Contracting Officer is the KO who has authority to make changes to contract terms, approve work, and receive notifications from MCMC.&lt;SEP&gt;Contracting Officer provides exercise support letters containing situation, mission, timelines, and approves MCMC resource plans.&lt;SEP&gt;The Contracting Officer issues orders, inserts requirements, approves waivers, consents to subcontracts, and directs adjustments in the contract.&lt;SEP&gt;Contracting Officer approves payments, exercises options, requests audits, and determines amounts due in case of non-submission.&lt;SEP&gt;Contracting Officer directs performance, receives notifications, authorizes orders, and handles adjustments and terminations.&lt;SEP&gt;Authorized individual responsible for approving changes, modifications, and resolutions of contractual problems, with authority remaining solely with this role.&lt;SEP&gt;Contracting Officer provides written authorization to MCMC for utilizing ancillary vendor support services.&lt;SEP&gt;The government official designated to receive written notifications from the Contractor regarding delivery or servicing of radioactive materials, changes in hazardous material composition, and related safety data submissions.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-f918f57232ad428f5920d4c98f0af702&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b535073f97c759a4e2ee7105ea8bc467&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b825754de20bbf2c5befd6a79730280e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2829fe507a5073eafb2e5fb0cc5e85c9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-46778545759b6a3b0240557a9acb9577&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-93752a7bd8aca85ef0ce5fea3701dc32&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-55bcb4486837a866d3ae601a0bfee839&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e8f1210c8fd617812bffc0e6bfaef07&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2edf7351f7d27be2ca8809d7ac16a11d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cf666a8ded534eb47b7eede4412a01f1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2fcdd71246fc4a058f5f995cbe6b3531&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-386066b546b82c7b89bda0ef90b3a5f2</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="MIL-STD 129">
  <ns0:data key="d0">MIL-STD 129</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">MIL-STD 129 specifies marking and labeling requirements for items containing radioactive materials in the latest revision in effect on the date of the contract.&lt;SEP&gt;The military standard for marking and labeling containers of items containing radioactive materials.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-b535073f97c759a4e2ee7105ea8bc467&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="FAR 23.601(d)">
  <ns0:data key="d0">FAR 23.601(d)</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">FAR 23.601(d) provides guidance on the number of days required in advance for delivery or servicing to obtain licenses and notify personnel for safety precautions.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Clause 52.229-8 Taxes-Foreign Cost-Reimbursement Contracts">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Clause 52.229-8 Taxes-Foreign Cost-Reimbursement Contracts</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">clause</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Clause 52.229-8 addresses taxes and duties from which the United States Government or the Contractor is exempt under foreign agreements or laws, and requires payment or credit for foreign tax credits reducing Federal income tax liability.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="United States Government">
  <ns0:data key="d0">United States Government</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">organization</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">The United States Government is exempt from certain foreign taxes and duties by agreement and receives reimbursements or credits related to tax liabilities under the contract.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Clause 52.243-2 Changes-Cost-Reimbursement">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Clause 52.243-2 Changes-Cost-Reimbursement</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">clause</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Clause 52.243-2 allows the Contracting Officer to make changes in drawings, designs, specifications, shipment methods, packing, or delivery places, with equitable adjustments to cost, schedule, fixed fee, and other terms.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Subcontract">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Subcontract</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">concept</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Subcontract must include the substance of specified clauses if exceeding certain thresholds and not for commercial products or services.&lt;SEP&gt;A subcontract is any contract entered into by a subcontractor to furnish supplies or services for the prime contract, including purchase orders and modifications.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-752a3887d9e623b57dee7c9de056ce5b</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Approved Purchasing System">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Approved Purchasing System</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">concept</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">An approved purchasing system is a Contractor's system reviewed and approved in accordance with Part 44 of the Federal Acquisition Regulation.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841045</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Consent to Subcontract">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Consent to Subcontract</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">requirement</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Consent to subcontract is the Contracting Officer's written consent for the Contractor to enter into a particular subcontract, required under specified conditions.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Clause 52.244-2 Subcontracts">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Clause 52.244-2 Subcontracts</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">clause</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Clause 52.244-2 defines terms, requires consent for certain subcontracts based on type and value, specifies notification procedures, and includes provisions for audits and reviews.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Micro-Purchase Threshold">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Micro-Purchase Threshold</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">concept</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">The Micro-Purchase Threshold is defined in FAR Subpart 2.1 and applies to subcontract approvals and Government review.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Clause 52.246-20 Warranty of Services">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Clause 52.246-20 Warranty of Services</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">clause</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Clause 52.246-20 warrants that services performed under the contract are free from defects and conform to requirements at acceptance, with provisions for correction, reperformance, or equitable adjustments.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Acceptance">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Acceptance</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">concept</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Acceptance is the act by an authorized Government representative assuming ownership of supplies or approving services as partial or complete contract performance.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Clause 52.252-2 Clauses Incorporated by Reference">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Clause 52.252-2 Clauses Incorporated by Reference</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">clause</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Clause 52.252-2 incorporates clauses by reference with the same force as full text, accessible electronically at specified addresses.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Clause 252.203-7004 Display of Hotline Posters">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Clause 252.203-7004 Display of Hotline Posters</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">clause</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Clause 252.203-7004 requires the Contractor to display DoD fraud, waste, and abuse hotline posters in work areas, with options for non-U.S. performance and inclusion in subcontracts exceeding specified thresholds.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Department of Defense">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Department of Defense</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">organization</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">The Department of Defense provides guidance and directives governing Navy and Marine Corps activities.&lt;SEP&gt;The Department of Defense uses DPAS as its property management system and Accountable Property System of Record.&lt;SEP&gt;Department of Defense provides antiterrorism/force protection awareness information and guidance to contractors.&lt;SEP&gt;The Department of Defense funds contracts and requires display of its fraud hotline poster in work areas performing under DoD contracts.&lt;SEP&gt;Department of Defense is the DoD whose facilities require MCMC personnel identification and restricts employment of active duty personnel by MCMC.&lt;SEP&gt;Department of Defense is associated with DD Form 254, DFARS, and supply sources.&lt;SEP&gt;Department of Defense establishes civilian employee pay rates, including differential pay for areas of imminent danger.&lt;SEP&gt;Department of Defense issues policies, instructions, and directives for environmental compliance in contractor operations.&lt;SEP&gt;Department of Defense provides subcontracting goals and procurement history basis for the acquisition.&lt;SEP&gt;Department of Defense establishes subcontracting goals based on overall goals and procurement history for the acquisition.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-939c604b9027c9cc38a7fb31f4c86c29&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-752a3887d9e623b57dee7c9de056ce5b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b825754de20bbf2c5befd6a79730280e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1b912387d0abf83a18f9cd19906dc41e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2fcdd71246fc4a058f5f995cbe6b3531&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b8875a30a8284afacba5893b8971b2b3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bee5e6b5db1fe2dc611fc5fc2b227a51&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-386066b546b82c7b89bda0ef90b3a5f2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d89c19e067243fa311d34bfc3fa99c70</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="DoD Office of the Inspector General">
  <ns0:data key="d0">DoD Office of the Inspector General</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">organization</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">The DoD Office of the Inspector General prepares the fraud, waste, and abuse hotline poster for display in contract work areas.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Department of Homeland Security">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Department of Homeland Security</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">organization</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">The Department of Homeland Security requires display of its fraud hotline poster for contracts funded by disaster relief funds performed in the United States.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="United States">
  <ns0:data key="d0">United States</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">location</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">United States includes the fifty states, District of Columbia, commonwealths, territories, and minor outlying islands as defined in clauses.&lt;SEP&gt;The United States includes the 50 States, the District of Columbia, and outlying areas, where hotline posters must be displayed for certain contracts.&lt;SEP&gt;United States enters into agreements with foreign governments applicable to contract performance in foreign ports.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-d89c19e067243fa311d34bfc3fa99c70&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-752a3887d9e623b57dee7c9de056ce5b</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Washington, DC">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Washington, DC</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">location</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Washington, DC is the location for obtaining DHS fraud hotline posters from the Office of Inspector General.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Clause 252.204-7007 Alternate A, Annual Representations and Certifications">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Clause 252.204-7007 Alternate A, Annual Representations and Certifications</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">clause</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Clause 252.204-7007 substitutes paragraphs for FAR 52.204-8, allowing use of System for Award Management representations and specifying applicable representations like 252.204-7016 and others.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="System for Award Management">
  <ns0:data key="d0">System for Award Management</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">technology</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">System for Award Management is a database where offerors maintain active registrations and complete annual representations and certifications electronically.&lt;SEP&gt;The System for Award Management is a database where Offerors maintain active registrations and representations applicable to solicitations.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-752a3887d9e623b57dee7c9de056ce5b</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Federal Acquisition Regulation">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Federal Acquisition Regulation</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Federal Acquisition Regulation (FAR) governs the development of the Supply/Maintenance Annual Spend Plan.&lt;SEP&gt;Federal Acquisition Regulation is defined by the acronym FAR.&lt;SEP&gt;The Federal Acquisition Regulation governs purchasing systems, subcontract consents, thresholds, and other contract provisions referenced throughout the clauses.&lt;SEP&gt;Federal Acquisition Regulation is the regulatory source for clauses, thresholds, and procedures referenced throughout the contract.&lt;SEP&gt;The Federal Acquisition Regulation (FAR) specifies thresholds and exceptions for certified cost or pricing data in solicitations.&lt;SEP&gt;Federal Acquisition Regulation is the FAR referenced for clauses such as 52.216-8 on fixed fee and invoicing procedures.&lt;SEP&gt;The regulation providing thresholds for subcontract values, such as FAR 22.1303(a) and FAR 22.1408(a), applicable on the date of subcontract award.&lt;SEP&gt;Federal Acquisition Regulation provides guidelines on late proposals and other procurement rules referenced in the RFP.&lt;SEP&gt;The Federal Acquisition Regulation is the primary regulation for federal procurement, with clauses numbered 52.xxx incorporated by reference in the contract.&lt;SEP&gt;Regulation referenced in clauses for allowable cost, payment, fast pay, and other contractual provisions.&lt;SEP&gt;Federal Acquisition Regulation provides the regulatory framework for acquisitions, including thresholds like FAR 30.201-4(b) for Cost Accounting Standards and FAR 4.1201 for representations in the System for Award Management.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-6b04b67f7f379aa858c2a82b29df69a0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b535073f97c759a4e2ee7105ea8bc467&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-33458028830a7ae0043a51d8a7a1e726&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c6c8cc3b4b40997aa333b8fb93d6c6b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8efbcbadad92a347ffdc7b5c1e34b2f7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e63c0b2b2602443bbfc148f7717d7ee5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-46778545759b6a3b0240557a9acb9577&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-55bcb4486837a866d3ae601a0bfee839&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e8f1210c8fd617812bffc0e6bfaef07&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-386066b546b82c7b89bda0ef90b3a5f2</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Defense Federal Acquisition Regulation Supplement">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Defense Federal Acquisition Regulation Supplement</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Defense Federal Acquisition Regulation Supplement is a regulatory supplement referenced for thresholds in subcontract awards.&lt;SEP&gt;The Defense Federal Acquisition Regulation Supplement specifies thresholds for including clauses in subcontracts, such as DFARS 203.1004(b)(2)(ii).&lt;SEP&gt;The Defense Federal Acquisition Regulation Supplement provides additional clauses for Department of Defense contracts, with clauses numbered 252.xxx incorporated by reference in the contract.&lt;SEP&gt;DFARS governs aspects such as payment timelines for DoD supply sources and authorization terminations.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-4c6c8cc3b4b40997aa333b8fb93d6c6b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2fcdd71246fc4a058f5f995cbe6b3531&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-752a3887d9e623b57dee7c9de056ce5b</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Contractor">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Contractor</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">organization</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">The Contractor is responsible for crane operations, fuel delivery, maintenance of vehicles and equipment, and compliance with various standards and regulations.&lt;SEP&gt;The Contractor is responsible for performing maintenance, repairs, operations, and compliance activities for NTVE, MHE, WHE, and related equipment as specified in the contract.&lt;SEP&gt;Contractor is required to comply with clauses, include provisions in subcontracts, and maintain plans for essential services.&lt;SEP&gt;Contractor is the party responsible for submitting cost proposals, performing services, complying with clauses, and settling subcontractor amounts.&lt;SEP&gt;The entity responsible for abiding by equal opportunity clauses, inserting terms in subcontracts, listing hazardous materials, notifying about radioactive materials, and complying with labor standards under the contract.&lt;SEP&gt;The Contractor performs services under the contract, provides notices for radioactive materials, requests waivers, obtains consents for subcontracts, warrants service quality, displays hotline posters, and handles tax credits.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-b535073f97c759a4e2ee7105ea8bc467&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9fdacd5fbf292ea850730c0c323f0873&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-752a3887d9e623b57dee7c9de056ce5b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-55bcb4486837a866d3ae601a0bfee839&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27cca63c94e6ea85e547a26e12b48a3c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="United States Internal Revenue Code">
  <ns0:data key="d0">United States Internal Revenue Code</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">The United States Internal Revenue Code (Title 26, U.S. Code) addresses Federal income tax liability reductions due to foreign tax credits from reimbursed payments under the contract.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="FAR Subpart 2.1">
  <ns0:data key="d0">FAR Subpart 2.1</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">section</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">FAR Subpart 2.1 defines key terms such as subcontract, micro-purchase threshold, and other contract-related concepts used in the clauses.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Coast Guard">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Coast Guard</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">organization</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">The Coast Guard is an agency whose contract awards influence the simplified acquisition threshold for fixed-price subcontract consent requirements.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="National Aeronautics and Space Administration">
  <ns0:data key="d0">National Aeronautics and Space Administration</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">organization</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">The National Aeronautics and Space Administration is an agency referenced for determining subcontract consent thresholds based on the simplified acquisition threshold in its awarded contracts.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Simplified Acquisition Threshold">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Simplified Acquisition Threshold</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">concept</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">The Simplified Acquisition Threshold, as defined in FAR 2.101, sets limits for consent to fixed-price subcontracts depending on the awarding agency and total estimated contract cost.&lt;SEP&gt;Simplified Acquisition Threshold is a monetary limit defined in Federal Acquisition Regulation 2.101, used for subcontract inclusion requirements.&lt;SEP&gt;Simplified Acquisition Threshold is a monetary threshold referenced in multiple provisions to determine applicability of small business size standards, set-asides, and other acquisition procedures.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-e63c0b2b2602443bbfc148f7717d7ee5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-752a3887d9e623b57dee7c9de056ce5b</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Offeror">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Offeror</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">concept</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Offeror must provide representations, certifications, and plans as part of the solicitation response.&lt;SEP&gt;Offeror refers to the entity submitting the proposal, responsible for providing thorough past performance, cost/price information, and compliance with all solicitation requirements.&lt;SEP&gt;Offeror is the entity submitting a proposal or bid in response to the RFP, required to provide certifications and representations.&lt;SEP&gt;The Offeror responds to the solicitation by completing or referencing representations and certifications, including options via the System for Award Management.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-28d6e3bcda588a7e152c62f52269f946&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1b912387d0abf83a18f9cd19906dc41e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-752a3887d9e623b57dee7c9de056ce5b</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="FAR 52.204-7">
  <ns0:data key="d0">FAR 52.204-7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">clause</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">FAR 52.204-7 is a provision for the System for Award Management included in solicitations.&lt;SEP&gt;FAR 52.204-7 is the System for Award Management provision that applies when included in the solicitation, enabling use of SAM for representations.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-752a3887d9e623b57dee7c9de056ce5b</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="FAR 52.204-8">
  <ns0:data key="d0">FAR 52.204-8</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">clause</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">FAR 52.204-8 is a provision for annual representations and certifications, with substituted paragraphs in Alternate A.&lt;SEP&gt;FAR 52.204-8 is the Annual Representations and Certifications provision modified by Alternate A in Clause 252.204-7007 for this solicitation.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-752a3887d9e623b57dee7c9de056ce5b</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="252.204-7016">
  <ns0:data key="d0">252.204-7016</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">clause</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">252.204-7016 is a representation on covered defense telecommunications equipment or services applicable to all solicitations.&lt;SEP&gt;252.204-7016 is the representation regarding Covered Defense Telecommunications Equipment or Services, applicable to all solicitations as indicated in the SAM database.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-752a3887d9e623b57dee7c9de056ce5b</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="252.216-7008">
  <ns0:data key="d0">252.216-7008</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">clause</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">252.216-7008 is a provision for economic price adjustment on wage rates or material prices controlled by a foreign government, applicable to fixed-price contracts in foreign countries.&lt;SEP&gt;252.216-7008 addresses Economic Price Adjustment for Wage Rates or Material Prices Controlled by a Foreign Government, applicable to fixed-price supply and service contracts performed in foreign countries.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-752a3887d9e623b57dee7c9de056ce5b</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Disputes Clause">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Disputes Clause</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">clause</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Disputes clause governs failures to agree on final annual indirect cost rates as a dispute.&lt;SEP&gt;Disputes Clause is a contract provision that does not apply to the approval of process improvements.&lt;SEP&gt;The Disputes Clause resolves disagreements on adjustments from contract changes, requiring the Contractor to proceed despite disputes.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-55bcb4486837a866d3ae601a0bfee839&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d89c19e067243fa311d34bfc3fa99c70</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Limitation of Cost Clause">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Limitation of Cost Clause</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">clause</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">The Limitation of Cost Clause limits the Contractor's obligation to perform or incur costs beyond established points without contract modification.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841046</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Limitation of Funds Clause">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Limitation of Funds Clause</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">clause</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">The Limitation of Funds Clause applies to incrementally funded contracts, restricting performance until additional funds are allotted by modification.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="OMB No. 9000-0107">
  <ns0:data key="d0">OMB No. 9000-0107</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">requirement</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">OMB No. 9000-0107 is the control number associated with the notice requirements for radioactive materials in the contract clause.&lt;SEP&gt;The Office of Management and Budget control number associated with the information collection for notices regarding radioactive materials.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-b535073f97c759a4e2ee7105ea8bc467&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Accounting Classification Reference Number">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Accounting Classification Reference Number</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">concept</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Accounting Classification Reference Number is the ACRN used in task orders for funding values, cost reporting, and segregation by equipment ownership groups.&lt;SEP&gt;The Accounting Classification Reference Number (ACRN) is used in the Contractor's accounting system to track CAP, subcontracts, and task orders for Government review.&lt;SEP&gt;Accounting Classification Reference Number (ACRN) is associated with USMC and Navy for reporting and projections under Task Orders.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-939c604b9027c9cc38a7fb31f4c86c29&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-386066b546b82c7b89bda0ef90b3a5f2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="DHS Office of Inspector General">
  <ns0:data key="d0">DHS Office of Inspector General</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">organization</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">The DHS Office of Inspector General provides the fraud hotline poster for display in contracts funded by DHS disaster relief funds performed in the United States.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-411fd0fef03fc3d4fd825823982dd9d7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="MCPP-PHIL">
  <ns0:data key="d0">MCPP-PHIL</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">location</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">MCPP-PHIL is a program or service requiring specific authorizations and work at various facilities, primarily in Subic Bay Philippines, with operations governed by host nation labor laws and limited to Monday through Friday, 10 hours per day.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-PHIL is a prepositioning site in the Philippines lacking a supporting DLA fuel facility and requiring local fuel procurement.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-PHIL is a prepositioning program supported by MCMC for supply and medical management with a 24-month minimum shelf-life expiration for ashore sites.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-PHIL is an ashore prepositioning site associated with supply accounts and weekly class of supply reports.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-PHIL refers to the Maritime Prepositioning Ships Program in the Philippines, for which the MCMC maintains DSI inventories and provides reports.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-PHIL is a prepositioning program involving production periods for equipment maintenance, with specific requirements for fuel processing, COSIS, and shelf life criteria.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-PHIL is a location for establishing and maintaining DSI inventories using GCSS-MC Planner's Desktop.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-PHIL is a prepositioning site requiring maintenance during designated production periods, with specific elastomeric service life exemptions.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-PHIL is a prepositioning program location or site for retail accounts.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-PHIL is the Marine Corps Prepositioning Program in the Philippines, based in Subic Bay, requiring MCMC to handle import/export, compliance, and logistics.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-PHIL is a prepositioning program in the Philippines requiring 100% validation of SKOTs prior to shipment.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-PHIL is the Marine Corps Prepositioning Program site in the Philippines where AMALs are maintained, stored, replenished, and refreshed annually and every third year.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-PHIL is a program for which cost data is collected and reported using the Program Cost Summary.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-PHIL is the Philippines-specific component of the Marine Corps Prepositioning Program, involving operations in the USINDOPACOM area of responsibility, hiring of OCN personnel with approval, and compliance with ITAR and Export Administration Regulations.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-PHIL is the Maritime Prepositioning Program site in the Philippines, requiring shipment of materiel with 25 months or greater shelf life remaining.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-PHIL is the Marine Corps Prepositioning Program-Philippines requiring licensed commercial importer status, CRTE, and coordination for import/export clearances under local regulations.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-PHIL is a prepositioning program and exercise site where MCMC conducts operations, including equipment checks and support plans.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-PHIL is the specific preposition site where IT support positions are part of the Information Assurance Workforce.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-PHIL is a program for which Marine Corps Logistics Command and Blount Island Command personnel are responsible.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-c12bdd730383e0d5968b0354d37c6d8a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-68739860c42b764e52f9649ea16ed702&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-65833c099ebcc7aa1fccc5a1d930a7aa&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-89b1a9fa6c0722adcd478e665df09141&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c10c3b1cc4c0a5d44aa2c137a52eaf0b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8a136ea2c9ab7ea9bb718fd0abd010d4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-22de15a10ae9bfba6096cca855d5f78a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0395bdbad90a448875b2a66efe14f948&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a0a00a7bb666b381893da579a6b228c9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-13a4841aefad66042f059edb023e607b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a9aba44b05f751488f4a50faebf206cb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-67bad1bd73dd9a9a7549acb855ae5e55&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2829fe507a5073eafb2e5fb0cc5e85c9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-432adfa735f19522f81538c1e139e7a3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f918f57232ad428f5920d4c98f0af702&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8efbcbadad92a347ffdc7b5c1e34b2f7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-30ad74540c8224cf4aff1f3de36d3780&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2edf7351f7d27be2ca8809d7ac16a11d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="USINDOPACOM AO">
  <ns0:data key="d0">USINDOPACOM AO</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">location</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">USINDOPACOM AO is the area of responsibility encompassing countries including Philippines, Palau, Australia, Japan, Singapore, Korea, Malaysia, Papua New Guinea, Micronesia, and Indonesia.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Philippines">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Philippines</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">location</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Philippines is a country within the USINDOPACOM AO where MCPP-PHIL services are primarily conducted, particularly in Subic Bay.&lt;SEP&gt;The Philippines hosts the Marine Corps Prepositioning Program – Philippines in the Subic Bay Metropolitan Authority Freeport zone for humanitarian assistance and contingency operations.&lt;SEP&gt;Philippines hosts MCPP-PHIL operations, involving commercial import/export clearances under SBMA regulations and tax exemptions for equipment movement.&lt;SEP&gt;Philippines hosts MCPP-PHIL maintenance and repair activities, with annual baselined production plans created and updated quarterly.&lt;SEP&gt;Philippines is a host nation for MCPP-PHIL operations, where MCMC personnel must comply with local labor laws and other regulations.&lt;SEP&gt;The Philippines hosts prepositioned equipment for MCPP-PHIL with SKOT validation requirements.&lt;SEP&gt;Philippines hosts the Marine Corps Prepositioning Program Philippines.&lt;SEP&gt;Philippines is the location for MCPP-PHIL where Confirmation of Receipt is processed upon physical receipt.&lt;SEP&gt;Philippines is the specific location for annual maintenance, calibration, replenishment, and every third year refresh of MCPP-PHIL AMALs.&lt;SEP&gt;Philippines hosts MCPP-PHIL exercises, US Embassy for FPO/AP address, and joint inventories for KMI operations.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-f918f57232ad428f5920d4c98f0af702&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a9aba44b05f751488f4a50faebf206cb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-30e4e078d2ff5ac82b96140f8c79e3f2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-22de15a10ae9bfba6096cca855d5f78a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-30ad74540c8224cf4aff1f3de36d3780&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2edf7351f7d27be2ca8809d7ac16a11d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-73f90f99a53e4953f841f6b0275ecb2f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bee5e6b5db1fe2dc611fc5fc2b227a51&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-583182dd35a85d121fe43aee2e3cd0eb</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Subic Bay">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Subic Bay</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">location</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Subic Bay is a primary location in Philippines for MCPP-PHIL work at contractor, subcontractor, and government facilities.&lt;SEP&gt;Subic Bay is the site in the Philippines where equipment for the Marine Corps Prepositioning Program – Philippines is prepositioned and maintained.&lt;SEP&gt;Subic Bay is the primary location in the Philippines for MCPP-PHIL services at contractor, subcontractor, and government facilities.&lt;SEP&gt;Subic Bay in the Philippines is the location for MCPP-PHIL services, utilizing government provided facilities and equipment.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-73f90f99a53e4953f841f6b0275ecb2f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2edf7351f7d27be2ca8809d7ac16a11d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c12bdd730383e0d5968b0354d37c6d8a</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Surge Support Personnel">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Surge Support Personnel</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">section</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Surge Support Personnel is a section outlining requirements for MCMC to provide and staff three Surge Teams of five to seven members each, covering maintenance skills, deployable based on workload, and integrated into the on-island workforce when not deployed.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Surge Teams">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Surge Teams</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">requirement</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Surge Teams are groups of five to seven personnel encompassing maintenance skills across MCPP departments, deployable in part or whole, with utilization plans presented semi-annually.&lt;SEP&gt;Surge Teams are groups of five to seven members each, encompassing maintenance skills, deployable based on workload demands and incorporated into the workforce when not deployed.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-2edf7351f7d27be2ca8809d7ac16a11d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Equipment and Materiel Accountability">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Equipment and Materiel Accountability</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">section</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Equipment and Materiel Accountability is a section detailing MCMC's responsibility for maintaining strict accountability of government-owned equipment and supplies, including various supply accounts like General Account, Maintenance Float/Reparable Issue Point, and others associated with MPSRON, MCPP-PHIL, and on-island accounts.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Government Furnished Property">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Government Furnished Property</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">section</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Government Furnished Property is a section specifying MCMC's maintenance responsibilities for GFP, including office furniture, equipment, maintenance tools, and restrictions on use.&lt;SEP&gt;Government Furnished Property includes equipment and materials provided for use in performing contractual tasks under the Statement of Work.&lt;SEP&gt;Government Furnished Property is defined by the acronym GFP.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-73f90f99a53e4953f841f6b0275ecb2f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-46778545759b6a3b0240557a9acb9577&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="GFP">
  <ns0:data key="d0">GFP</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">concept</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">GFP refers to government-furnished property provided to MCMC for contract performance, which must be maintained in clean, operable condition, with MCMC responsible for repairs or replacements.&lt;SEP&gt;GFP refers to Government Furnished Property for which the successor assumes control and accountability from the incumbent upon government acceptance of joint inventory.&lt;SEP&gt;GFP is Government Furnished Property for accountability in Navy operations.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-6b04b67f7f379aa858c2a82b29df69a0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b6f17f0fbf6c678da23e588ab57f6900</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="SPOT LOA">
  <ns0:data key="d0">SPOT LOA</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">SPOT LOA is the Synchronized Predeployment Operational Tracker Letters of Authorization required for MCPP-PHIL and MCMC employees, including authorizations for specific countries in USINDOPACOM AO.&lt;SEP&gt;SPOT LOA is the Synchronized Predeployment Operational Tracker Letters of Authorization required for MCPP-PHIL employee access to specified countries.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-2edf7351f7d27be2ca8809d7ac16a11d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="MPSRON">
  <ns0:data key="d0">MPSRON</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">organization</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">MPSRON is associated with sub-custody accounts for prepositioned equipment and supplies under MCMC management.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="BICmd">
  <ns0:data key="d0">BICmd</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">organization</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">BICmd is referenced in contexts like Information Systems Management Office and command orders related to MCPP operations.&lt;SEP&gt;BICmd is a command location involving multiple intermediate and consumer level accounts with geographic dispersion.&lt;SEP&gt;BICmd is the organization coordinating with the U.S. Embassy for import/export clearances and receiving notifications and reports from the MCMC.&lt;SEP&gt;BICmd is the Blount Island Command that oversees prepositioning programs and coordinates with MCMC for sustainment and operations.&lt;SEP&gt;BICmd is a location where production maintenance occurs for Organic GFE and Prepositioned Military Equipment.&lt;SEP&gt;BICmd is responsible for using systems like QMSS and DAI for program-wide KPI monitoring and performance reviews.&lt;SEP&gt;BICmd Government personnel coordinate with LOGCOM for Repair and Return program services.&lt;SEP&gt;BICmd is designated as the Executive Agent for the Marine Corps Prepositioning Program, providing guidance, direction, oversight, and liaison.&lt;SEP&gt;BICmd operates temporary weapons facilities for storing weapons during MMC production.&lt;SEP&gt;BICmd uses the Program Cost Summary for performance monitoring and has policies in Command ISOs and SharePoint.&lt;SEP&gt;BICmd is associated with the organic account M92502 and participates in joint inventory efforts with MCMC.&lt;SEP&gt;BICmd is the Blount Island Command prescribing sub-inventories for sustainment blocks on non T-AKE ships.&lt;SEP&gt;BICmd is the organization overseeing KMI accounts, providing endorsements, and coordinating with MCMC for prepositioning operations.&lt;SEP&gt;BICmd provides resources and port operations for prepositioning support.&lt;SEP&gt;BICmd is the organization managing KMI where SF153 is delivered.&lt;SEP&gt;Blount Island Command (BICmd) is involved in work instructions, appointing personnel for weight handling programs, joint ISO 9001:2015 certification with MCMC, and overseeing command orders.&lt;SEP&gt;BICmd is the Base Installation Command associated with safety offices and tenant organizations supported by MCMC services.&lt;SEP&gt;BICmd oversees the logistics mission of managing and executing the Marine Corps Prepositioning Programs.&lt;SEP&gt;BICmd issues orders such as 4200.3 and involves contractors with whom the MCMC interfaces for technical meetings and information exchanges.&lt;SEP&gt;BICmd is a command organization at Blount Island supported by MCMC for voice, video, and data services.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-c12bdd730383e0d5968b0354d37c6d8a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b6f17f0fbf6c678da23e588ab57f6900&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cf666a8ded534eb47b7eede4412a01f1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-68739860c42b764e52f9649ea16ed702&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-65833c099ebcc7aa1fccc5a1d930a7aa&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5d0f24c6dd1ff5486bfe7491203ea801&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-93c4a54422e967728929a60f73e593e2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-22de15a10ae9bfba6096cca855d5f78a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4ef5ed78269155f4369ff9bd9b69ddc8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0395bdbad90a448875b2a66efe14f948&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-13a4841aefad66042f059edb023e607b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-67bad1bd73dd9a9a7549acb855ae5e55&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-432adfa735f19522f81538c1e139e7a3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f918f57232ad428f5920d4c98f0af702&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8efbcbadad92a347ffdc7b5c1e34b2f7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-30ad74540c8224cf4aff1f3de36d3780&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-93752a7bd8aca85ef0ce5fea3701dc32&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bee5e6b5db1fe2dc611fc5fc2b227a51&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f808346dbf233cd47e4c673a7cf87022</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Contract Reference Library">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Contract Reference Library</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">deliverable</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Contract Reference Library is a centralized document management system that MCMC must update and make available to the Government annually by February 1st, including reference manuals and publications.&lt;SEP&gt;The Contract Reference Library is an electronic collection of documents provided to offerors upon execution of a Non-Disclosure Agreement.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-33458028830a7ae0043a51d8a7a1e726</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="M6700425R0007">
  <ns0:data key="d0">M6700425R0007</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">M6700425R0007 is the draft RFP document outlining contract requirements for MCPP, including sections on personnel, equipment, and references.&lt;SEP&gt;M6700425R0007 is the solicitation number for the Draft RFP issued on 26 Feb 2026 as a Negotiated RFP.&lt;SEP&gt;M6700425R0007 is a draft Request for Proposal (RFP) for the Marine Corps Prepositioning Program Logistics Services Contract.&lt;SEP&gt;M6700425R0007 is the draft RFP document detailing contract line items from pages 21 to 34.&lt;SEP&gt;Solicitation number identifying the Draft RFP document.&lt;SEP&gt;M6700425R0007 is the identifier for the DRAFT RFP document outlining contract requirements.&lt;SEP&gt;M6700425R0007 is the Draft RFP document outlining the contract for MCPP support services.&lt;SEP&gt;M6700425R0007 is the contract number for the DRAFT RFP.&lt;SEP&gt;M6700425R0007 is a draft RFP document spanning multiple pages with contract clauses.&lt;SEP&gt;M6700425R0007 is the solicitation number for the Draft RFP issued by the United States Marine Corps.&lt;SEP&gt;M6700425R0007 is the draft RFP solicitation number for the contract covering pages 330 to 335.&lt;SEP&gt;M6700425R0007 is the DRAFT RFP document outlining requirements for Navy Watercraft maintenance and operations across pages 209 to 214.&lt;SEP&gt;M6700425R0007 is the solicitation number for the draft RFP.&lt;SEP&gt;The draft Request for Proposal (RFP) document referenced throughout the clauses, spanning multiple pages including 360 to 365 of 425.&lt;SEP&gt;M6700425R0007 is the identifier for the draft Request for Proposal (RFP) document outlining the acquisition requirements and evaluation processes.&lt;SEP&gt;M6700425R0007 is the solicitation number referenced throughout the draft RFP for the acquisition.&lt;SEP&gt;M6700425R0007 is the identifier for the DRAFT RFP document spanning multiple pages.&lt;SEP&gt;M6700425R0007 is the solicitation number for the DRAFT RFP.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-282e59d5d28c9bf1f8c358524d50c08c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f6510cadeb544a78c12488882601935c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-939c604b9027c9cc38a7fb31f4c86c29&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3478ab61c9462db63588376af8a45cd2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-33458028830a7ae0043a51d8a7a1e726&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f0bef8ac155e28eb1ccd0095250383c3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d6887833d0f1a6398bb6c8fd6f72d5c8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2fcdd71246fc4a058f5f995cbe6b3531&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8aa129e6fff6d48e4dab5ab9c9d8c169&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6b04b67f7f379aa858c2a82b29df69a0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b535073f97c759a4e2ee7105ea8bc467&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-752a3887d9e623b57dee7c9de056ce5b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-73f90f99a53e4953f841f6b0275ecb2f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-386066b546b82c7b89bda0ef90b3a5f2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d89c19e067243fa311d34bfc3fa99c70&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-93752a7bd8aca85ef0ce5fea3701dc32&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1b912387d0abf83a18f9cd19906dc41e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bee5e6b5db1fe2dc611fc5fc2b227a51</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="MCO P4400.151">
  <ns0:data key="d0">MCO P4400.151</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">MCO P4400.151 is a Marine Corps order governing intermediate level inventory and sub-custody responsibilities.&lt;SEP&gt;MCO P4400.151 is a Marine Corps Order referenced for property record adjustments and supply documentation retention.&lt;SEP&gt;MCO P4400.151 is referenced for supply issuance procedures during MPF exercises on T-AKE ships.&lt;SEP&gt;MCO P4400.151 details procedures for receipt management, procurement of consumables, and requisitioning SECREPs.&lt;SEP&gt;MCO P4400.151 provides guidance on management of maritime prepositioned equipment and supplies.&lt;SEP&gt;MCO P4400.151 is a Marine Corps publication providing guidance on provisioning and supply support.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-abd2ceb311ce78c8a8c1fe38d11ee4f4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-67bad1bd73dd9a9a7549acb855ae5e55&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-22de15a10ae9bfba6096cca855d5f78a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bd3a05bb896b89de7fd366c654ad4a6b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-583182dd35a85d121fe43aee2e3cd0eb</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="UM 4000-125">
  <ns0:data key="d0">UM 4000-125</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">document</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">UM 4000-125 is a uniform manual referenced for property record adjustments.&lt;SEP&gt;UM 4000-125 is a document outlining procedures for supply validations, issue management, and materiel accountability.&lt;SEP&gt;UM 4000-125 is a unit manual governing inventory adjustments, supply transactions, and documentation.&lt;SEP&gt;UM 4000-125 is a manual addressing processing of discrepancies in supply management.&lt;SEP&gt;UM 4000-125 is a manual referenced for equipment redistributions, procurement, and requisition management.&lt;SEP&gt;UM 4000-125 is a manual on materiel management, inventory, and accountability procedures.&lt;SEP&gt;UM 4000-125 provides guidance on inventories, APSR transactions, and supply management.&lt;SEP&gt;UM 4000-125 is a user manual referenced for calibration control, modification control, TAV configuration, equipment records, corrective maintenance, cannibalization, and UUAM programs.&lt;SEP&gt;UM 4000-125 provides procedures for calibration services, recording inspections, maintenance, and testing of portable fire extinguishers.&lt;SEP&gt;UM 4000-125 is referenced for performing Limited Technical Inspections on ME and CESE assets.&lt;SEP&gt;UM 4000-125 provides guidance on Urgency of Need Designator delegation and repair parts management in layettes.&lt;SEP&gt;UM 4000-125 provides uniform procedures for supply support and exercise operations on T-AKE ships.&lt;SEP&gt;UM 4000-125 outlines retail supply and maintenance execution procedures, including transportation documentation.&lt;SEP&gt;UM 4000-125 is a technical manual used for corrective maintenance on MPE/S during the afloat phase.&lt;SEP&gt;UM 4000-125 provides procedures for LTIs and testing lower explosive levels on ME and CESE assets.&lt;SEP&gt;UM 4000-125 covers procedures for calibration services, cannibalization, quality control, and LTI for CESE.&lt;SEP&gt;UM 4000-125 provides guidance for documenting maintenance services on TAMCN IT assets within GCSS-MC.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-955c2fafc0e5a2a07e97130b42a872b5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-abd2ceb311ce78c8a8c1fe38d11ee4f4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-13a4841aefad66042f059edb023e607b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-67bad1bd73dd9a9a7549acb855ae5e55&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-22de15a10ae9bfba6096cca855d5f78a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-30ad74540c8224cf4aff1f3de36d3780&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-68739860c42b764e52f9649ea16ed702&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cf666a8ded534eb47b7eede4412a01f1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bd3a05bb896b89de7fd366c654ad4a6b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5d0f24c6dd1ff5486bfe7491203ea801&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e151c7682b4ed7c6cd2fcdc2e29ec22&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-89b1a9fa6c0722adcd478e665df09141&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c10c3b1cc4c0a5d44aa2c137a52eaf0b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-432adfa735f19522f81538c1e139e7a3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a0a00a7bb666b381893da579a6b228c9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-583182dd35a85d121fe43aee2e3cd0eb</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="MCPP-N">
  <ns0:data key="d0">MCPP-N</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">location</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">MCPP-N is a prepositioning site in Norway requiring physical receipt processing and materiel accountability.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-N is an ashore prepositioning site associated with supply accounts and reporting requirements.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-N is the Maritime Prepositioning Program site in Norway, requiring shipment of materiel with 25 months or greater shelf life remaining.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-N is a specific site in Norway where PMCS and Corrective Maintenance are performed only on COMM/ELEC assets.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-N is the Maritime Prepositioning Program - Navy involving prepositioned equipment.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-N is the Marine Corps Prepositioning Program in Norway, utilizing government provided facilities, equipment, and tools in the Trondelog region.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-N is a prepositioning program in Norway requiring validation of SKOTs and management of crew served weapons.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-N is the Marine Corps Prepositioning Program site in Norway where AMALs are maintained, stored, replenished, and refreshed annually and every third year.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-N is a program for which cost data is collected and reported using the Program Cost Summary.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-N refers to the Maritime Prepositioning Ships Program in Norway, for which the MCMC maintains DSI inventories, participates in validations, and provides specific reports and notifications.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-N is the Marine Corps Prepositioning Program in Norway, supporting prepositioning of sensitive communications equipment and crew-served weapons.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-N is referenced in association with prepositioned equipment and supplies managed under the MCMC's custodial responsibilities.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-N refers to the site in Norway where DSI Authorization Letters are provided for COMM/ELEC equipment if required.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-N is the Marine Corps Prepositioning Program-Norway involving specific requirements for foreign military equipment clearance, host nation approvals, and weekly reporting.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-N is a program for which Marine Corps Logistics Command and Blount Island Command personnel are responsible.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-N is a prepositioning program site where MCMC conducts KMI local elements operations including inventories and accountability.&lt;SEP&gt;MCPP-N is a land-based prepositioning site included in manning and operational locations.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-f918f57232ad428f5920d4c98f0af702&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6b04b67f7f379aa858c2a82b29df69a0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-67bad1bd73dd9a9a7549acb855ae5e55&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c12bdd730383e0d5968b0354d37c6d8a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a9aba44b05f751488f4a50faebf206cb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8efbcbadad92a347ffdc7b5c1e34b2f7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2829fe507a5073eafb2e5fb0cc5e85c9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-22de15a10ae9bfba6096cca855d5f78a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-30ad74540c8224cf4aff1f3de36d3780&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-68739860c42b764e52f9649ea16ed702&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-93752a7bd8aca85ef0ce5fea3701dc32&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-65833c099ebcc7aa1fccc5a1d930a7aa&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-89b1a9fa6c0722adcd478e665df09141&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c10c3b1cc4c0a5d44aa2c137a52eaf0b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-432adfa735f19522f81538c1e139e7a3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a0a00a7bb666b381893da579a6b228c9</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="NSD">
  <ns0:data key="d0">NSD</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">location</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">NSD is a facility where MCPP-PHIL services require work, along with various contractor, subcontractor, and government facilities.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="PPSP">
  <ns0:data key="d0">PPSP</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">deliverable</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">PPSP is the Program Personnel Support Plan, a CDRL deliverable presented semi-annually including organizational chart, personnel roster, and capacity analysis.&lt;SEP&gt;PPSP identifies personnel including QIs, PCAs, and QM for MCPP quality requirements.&lt;SEP&gt;PPSP is a semi-annual plan in which the MCMC presents an anticipated Surge Team utilization plan as identified in paragraph 1.H.2.b.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-432adfa735f19522f81538c1e139e7a3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2edf7351f7d27be2ca8809d7ac16a11d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="General Account">
  <ns0:data key="d0">General Account</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">concept</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">General Account (GA) (MMV200) maintains consumable materials with demand-based stock computations and quarterly recommended stock levels.&lt;SEP&gt;General Account is a retail level supply account managed by the MCMC for the program.&lt;SEP&gt;General Account (GA) is an intermediate level supply account managed by the MCMC for materiel accountability in the MCPP program.&lt;SEP&gt;General Account is defined by the acronym GA.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-46778545759b6a3b0240557a9acb9577&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2edf7351f7d27be2ca8809d7ac16a11d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8efbcbadad92a347ffdc7b5c1e34b2f7</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Reparable Issue Point">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Reparable Issue Point</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">concept</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Reparable Issue Point (RIP) is a maintenance float supply account with associated sub-floats, managed by the MCMC.&lt;SEP&gt;Reparable Issue Point is defined by the acronym RIP.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-46778545759b6a3b0240557a9acb9577&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="GFE">
  <ns0:data key="d0">GFE</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">concept</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">GFE is Government Furnished Equipment listed in Contract Attachment 6a, for which the MCMC provides normal maintenance and repair, except for IT equipment.&lt;SEP&gt;GFE is Government Furnished Equipment including organic items requiring maintenance and corrosion control.&lt;SEP&gt;GFE refers to Government Furnished Equipment used by the Contractor for dispensing Government procured fuel in NTVE/MHE.&lt;SEP&gt;GFE refers to Government Furnished Equipment for which the successor assumes control and accountability from the incumbent upon government acceptance of joint inventory.&lt;SEP&gt;GFE is Government Furnished Equipment requiring accountability in Navy supply methodology.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-6b04b67f7f379aa858c2a82b29df69a0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b6f17f0fbf6c678da23e588ab57f6900&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27cca63c94e6ea85e547a26e12b48a3c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f808346dbf233cd47e4c673a7cf87022</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="MCEN">
  <ns0:data key="d0">MCEN</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">technology</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">MCEN is the Marine Corps Enterprise Network on which government-provided computers operate for official business, with restrictions on MCMC computer usage.&lt;SEP&gt;MCEN is the Marine Corps Enterprise Network providing garrison support through regionalized operations.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0395bdbad90a448875b2a66efe14f948</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="POL">
  <ns0:data key="d0">POL</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">concept</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">POL refers to Petroleum, Oils, and Lubricants included as sustainment supplies in shipping containers for prepositioned materiel.&lt;SEP&gt;POL refers to petroleum, oil, lubricants, and fuels provided by the Government to support MCMC maintenance efforts.&lt;SEP&gt;POL stands for Petroleum, Oils, and Lubricants that must be replaced for all Navy Watercraft, LARCs, and ABLTS every ship cycle.&lt;SEP&gt;POL is Petroleum, Oils, and Lubricants managed during embarkation and debarkation.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-93752a7bd8aca85ef0ce5fea3701dc32&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d6887833d0f1a6398bb6c8fd6f72d5c8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f808346dbf233cd47e4c673a7cf87022</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Rights in Data">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Rights in Data</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">section</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Rights in Data is section 1.L asserting Government ownership of all data associated with the MCPP and requiring MCMC to provide annual access to contract documentation.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Applicable Publications/Source Documents">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Applicable Publications/Source Documents</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">section</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Applicable Publications/Source Documents is section 1.M listing supplemental source documents and references that guide clarification of disputes under the SOW.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Blount Island Command">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Blount Island Command</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">organization</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Blount Island Command is responsible for conducting continental United States support for the Marine Corps Prepositioning Program at Blount Island, Jacksonville, Florida.&lt;SEP&gt;Blount Island Command is the command overseeing security instructions, orders, and directives that MCMC personnel must adhere to while on Blount Island.&lt;SEP&gt;Blount Island Command governs operations and administration of systems like QMSS for KPI reporting and performance reviews.&lt;SEP&gt;Blount Island Command develops Squadron Level Plans for the MPF program based on the approved Prepositioning Objective.&lt;SEP&gt;Blount Island Command is referenced in the context of Marine Corps prepositioning and logistics operations.&lt;SEP&gt;Blount Island Command issues various command orders (CmdO) that govern MCPP operations, including maintenance management and quality standards.&lt;SEP&gt;Blount Island Command is an organization with cognizant personnel charged with responsibility for the MPS Program, MCPP-N, and MCPP-PHIL.&lt;SEP&gt;Blount Island Command is the BlCmd that determines facility closures for hurricanes or foul weather and directs MCMC personnel actions.&lt;SEP&gt;Blount Island Command deploys personnel and resources in support of USMC/USN exercises utilizing MPE/S as outlined in Exercise Support Letters.&lt;SEP&gt;Blount Island Command is the facility hosting the Industry Day and site visit for the solicitation.&lt;SEP&gt;Military installation in Jacksonville, FL, serving as the site for the Contracts Office Code 902.&lt;SEP&gt;Blount Island Command is a facility of the U.S. Marine Corps located at 5880 Channel View Blvd., Jacksonville, FL 32226-3404.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-6b04b67f7f379aa858c2a82b29df69a0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-33458028830a7ae0043a51d8a7a1e726&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-30e4e078d2ff5ac82b96140f8c79e3f2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2829fe507a5073eafb2e5fb0cc5e85c9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5fcb066f3ce0c1cfffc65441135b96e1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e8f1210c8fd617812bffc0e6bfaef07&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-38be7e49aefd10e870f45cb648f7d79d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2edf7351f7d27be2ca8809d7ac16a11d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-73f90f99a53e4953f841f6b0275ecb2f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bee5e6b5db1fe2dc611fc5fc2b227a51&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-386066b546b82c7b89bda0ef90b3a5f2</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="MARCORLOGCOM">
  <ns0:data key="d0">MARCORLOGCOM</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">organization</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">MARCORLOGCOM is the Marine Corps Logistics Command issuing orders related to inventory control, accountable officers, and garrison property management.&lt;SEP&gt;MARCORLOGCOM supports DoD biennial asset inventory for ISO containers.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-abd2ceb311ce78c8a8c1fe38d11ee4f4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="Government">
  <ns0:data key="d0">Government</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">organization</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">Government directs MCMC activities, approves adjustments, receives reports and forms, and provides guidance on inventory and production operations.&lt;SEP&gt;Government receives nominations, reports, and coordinates replenishments and exercises with MCMC.&lt;SEP&gt;The Government receives inventory results and oversees compliance with various requirements and deliverables from the MCMC.&lt;SEP&gt;The Government provides approvals, detailed plans, and reviews reports from the MCMC.&lt;SEP&gt;Government receives reports, notifications, and approvals related to inventory, maintenance, and production from MCMC.&lt;SEP&gt;Government refers to the contracting authority, including DoD, Department of the Navy, and Marine Corps entities, responsible for providing property, approvals, and publications under the MCPP contract.&lt;SEP&gt;The Government conducts investigations, approves procedures, determines operator eligibility, and oversees contract compliance.&lt;SEP&gt;The Government conducts inspections, audits, evaluations, and provides requirements for NTVE, MHE, WHE maintenance and operations, including inventory and policy oversight.&lt;SEP&gt;Government is the party that reimburses costs, issues orders, audits submissions, and executes understandings for final indirect cost rates.&lt;SEP&gt;Government is the contracting authority that obligates funds for task orders, provides base support including facilities and utilities, approves travel and process improvements, and holds title to reimbursed contractor-acquired property.&lt;SEP&gt;The Government conducts the Site Visit, answers questions, evaluates proposals, and provides guidance on OCI and surveys.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-abd2ceb311ce78c8a8c1fe38d11ee4f4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a9aba44b05f751488f4a50faebf206cb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-67bad1bd73dd9a9a7549acb855ae5e55&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9fdacd5fbf292ea850730c0c323f0873&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-22de15a10ae9bfba6096cca855d5f78a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-55bcb4486837a866d3ae601a0bfee839&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27cca63c94e6ea85e547a26e12b48a3c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bd3a05bb896b89de7fd366c654ad4a6b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f121013aeb8c98e8b0609d68d89b74e5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d89c19e067243fa311d34bfc3fa99c70</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="KO">
  <ns0:data key="d0">KO</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">person</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">KO is the Contracting Officer who relieves the MCMC of asset responsibilities and arranges technical or industrial repair services when needed.&lt;SEP&gt;The KO is the Contracting Officer who designates priorities, approves repairs, receives notifications, and manages contract modifications for NTVE maintenance.&lt;SEP&gt;KO is the Contracting Officer who issues task orders, approves travel, and manages contract closeouts and notifications.&lt;SEP&gt;The KO is the contracting officer who receives copies of agreements, may terminate the contract for convenience to avoid OCI, and approves publicity releases.&lt;SEP&gt;KO is the Contracting Officer who approves standard operating procedures, determines operator eligibility after incidents, and authorizes repairs and part exchanges.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-9fdacd5fbf292ea850730c0c323f0873&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b6f17f0fbf6c678da23e588ab57f6900&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27cca63c94e6ea85e547a26e12b48a3c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d89c19e067243fa311d34bfc3fa99c70</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841047</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
<ns0:node id="COR">
  <ns0:data key="d0">COR</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d1">person</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d2">COR is a government role interacting with designated MCMC quality personnel.&lt;SEP&gt;COR is the Contracting Officer's Representative to be notified by the MCMC when additional tools or equipment are required for maintenance.&lt;SEP&gt;COR is the Contracting Officer's Representative who approves temporary lodging, coordinates privileges, and receives reports from MCMC.&lt;SEP&gt;COR coordinates accounting data, receives reports, and provides direction on maintenance tasks.&lt;SEP&gt;COR provides approvals for deviations, receives notifications, and is informed of schedule jeopardies and non-conformances.&lt;SEP&gt;COR is Contracting Officer's Representative approving maintenance extensions and directions.&lt;SEP&gt;Contracting Officer’s Representative (COR) receives submissions such as appointment letters, status reports, plans, and has access to files for QCP.&lt;SEP&gt;COR is the Contracting Officer's Representative responsible for requesting unscheduled fuel delivery services.&lt;SEP&gt;The COR receives copies of joint inventory results, detailed causative research on discrepancies, and written plans for statistical sampling during contract transition.&lt;SEP&gt;COR is the Navy Contracting Officer's Representative to whom MCMC submits various reports, plans, estimates, and assessments.</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d3">chunk-f918f57232ad428f5920d4c98f0af702&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-48caa545ec007aaf46c9abe9ec8c0c78&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b6f17f0fbf6c678da23e588ab57f6900&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f736781b685dec5629d8433e71c666e4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27cca63c94e6ea85e547a26e12b48a3c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-85b50b451f72c11f155dc39b516d8dd3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5d0f24c6dd1ff5486bfe7491203ea801&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-432adfa735f19522f81538c1e139e7a3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-93c4a54422e967728929a60f73e593e2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f808346dbf233cd47e4c673a7cf87022</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d4">M6700425R0007 MCPP II DRAFT RFP 23 MAY 25.pdf</ns0:data>
  <ns0:data key="d5">1759841048</ns0:data>
</ns0:node>
